sudden onset fever, chills, fatigue, transient maculopapular rash constant polyarthralgia/arthritis of small joints (hands, wrists, ankles, feet); leucopenia and mild thrombocytopenia. neurological, cardiac, and hepatic complications rare . the acute stage in infants and young children can be atypical (epidermolysis, myocarditis, or encephalitis), but is rarely fatal. infected neonates (mother-to-child transmission) are at a high risk of severe encephalopathy and death. chronic inflammatory joint symptoms were observed in up to 50% of adult cases, and after 2 years in some outbreaks.
sudden onset fever (may be diphasic), headache, myalgia, arthralgia, anorexia, dizziness, chills, and photophobia. also nausea, vomiting, diarrhea, epigastric and eye pain, conjunctivitis, and meningitis have been reported. recently, spontaneous hemorrhagic phenomena were reported in human cases. the disease is self-limiting, there are no reports of orov related deaths.
