ingestion of tapeworm eggs from feces of foxes, dogs, and cats or contaminated fomites. there is no person-to-person transmission.
obligate intracellular, pleomorphic bacteria of the family anaplasmataceae, which invade host leukocytes. ehrlichia chaffeensis infects mononuclear phagocytes; e. ewingii and anaplasma phagocytophilum infects neutrophils. e. canis may cause human disease in venezuela. in 2009 an e. murislike organism was discovered in usa. neorickettsia sennetsu causes sennetsu fever.
fa staining of frozen skin sections taken from the nape of the neck, or postmortem brain tissue; rt-pcr on saliva, skin or brain biopsy or buccal swab; serology; cell culture or mouse inoculation from saliva, skin, or brain.
intravenous, intramuscular, and intralesional application of pentavalent antimonials; also miltefosine is being tested for its efficacy. topical treatment options are: paramomycin, ketoconazole, and thermotherapy.
